post_text:
The 5th annual Stephen Stewart speech and debate tournament will be held online September 25-27. #MIlpitasHS speech and debate team, led by teacher/advisor Charles Schletzbaum, is actively recruiting volunteers and celebrity judges.

A 1-day commitment preferred. There are 2 rounds on Friday, 5 Saturday, and 4-6 rounds on Sunday depending on the event.

This tournament funds almost all of the debate activities throught the year. The late Stephen Stewart founded the team in 2008, but suffered a heart attack at Leland HS at a tournament, and we do this tournament in memory of his contributions. So far we have entries from 10 states. Please contact Charles Schletzbaum at cschletzbaum@musd.org for more details on how to volunteer.

WE are #MUSDfamily and WE will continue to help one another to get through this together!

September is Suicide Prevention Awareness Month and September 10th is World Suicide Prevention day.
Suicide is preventable! Youth outcomes change by having ONE positive adult relationship in their lives. Thank you for all you do to care for our students and each other; there is hope.
This is a list our #MUSD Mental Health and Wellness Staff compiled of Suicide Prevention Facts, Tips, and Resources for how to engage in the conversation around suicide prevention: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1jrZ7y2zyzIAbhEh_IJUeXsWTE_70qisNYSiO0YrffIQ/edit?usp=sharing

WE are #MUSDfamily and WE will continue to help one another to get through this together!

Santa Clara County's Office of Immigrant Relations kicks off #WelcomingWeek2020 next week by hosting virtual events from September 12-20, with this year's theme of #CreatingHomeTogether

Activities include FREE virtual legal consultations, guided family wellness activity in English & Spanish, three panel discussions with guests focused on immigrant resiliency, immigrants as essential workers, and honoring immigrant contributions. In addition, there will be available resources for #DREAMERs and immigrant youth as well as a virtual art gallery which will highlight the work of immigrant artists.

Some activities require advanced registration. All registration links can be found here: https://linktr.ee/OIR

WE are #MUSDfamily!

Fifty-seven years ago today, Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. delivered his iconic "I Have a Dream" address at the March on Washington.

Milpitas Unified School District commemorates that historic day of August 28, 1963 at the Lincoln Memorial in Washington, D.C.

To learn more about Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. and his "I Have a Dream" address, please follow this link: https://kinginstitute.stanford.edu/king-papers/documents/i-have-dream-address-delivered-march-washington-jobs-and-freedom

#MUSD #MUSDfamily

A Spare the Air Alert is in effect today, August 20 through Sunday, August 23! Burning wood, manufactured fire logs or any other solid fuel is banned, both indoors and outdoors. post_text:
Join #MUSD at the Silicon Valley Leadership Group’s virtual Education Summit 2020: Equity, Education and Talent Development Post-COVID on August 14 from 8:30am-12pm.

How are teachers and school administrators planning to start school in the fall? What are state legislators doing to ensure a safe, equitable education environment? What does the future of work, and learning and development look like in the wake of COVID-19, in the aftermath of George Floyd?

#EducationSummit2020 will feature key decision makers across education, government, and business in interactive sessions to address your questions, as well as topic-based networking rooms - all capstoned by a keynote from Becky Pringle, VP of the nation’s largest union, the #NationalEducationAssociation.

We hope to see you there! Register at https://www.svlg.org/event/education-summit/?instance_id=1099

post_text:
#MUSD District Leaders will host a series of Parent / Guardian Q&A's on the district's 2020-21 phasing in plan for parents / guardians of elementary, middle school, and high school students.

Simply fill out our Google registration form, submit your questions, and you will then receive the Zoom log-in information. The log-in can be used for any of the six Q&A meeting dates. Each session will run from 6:30 p.m. to 8 p.m. For elementary, the dates are Tuesday, July 14 and Thursday, July 16. For middle school, the dates are Tuesday, July 21 and Thursday, July 23. For high school, the dates are Tuesday, July 28 and Thursday, July 30.

We look forward to hearing from you and helping to answer any questions you may have on the 2020-21 school year.

WE are #MUSDfamily and WE will help one another to get through this together!

shared_text:
Councilmember Karina Dominguez
July 11 at 11:18 AM ·

Our office is proud to partner with Coronacovery. A youth lead organization in Milpitas who is helping our most vulnerable families.

Together, we will be delivering groceries, diapers, and any other essential items to seniors and families in need.

It was a very hot morning, but it was great to volunteer with Second Harvest Food Bank, Milpitas Unified School District, Coronacovery and many other volunteers. Thank you for being here this morning and helping our families. Together, we will move Milpitas forward. Together, we will rise above this virus. #teamcommunity #WeAreMilpitas #milpitas #milpitastrong #CoronaCovery #livewithintention

Please consider making a donation to their organization by visiting https://www.gofundme.com/f/coronacovery?utm_medium=copy_link&utm_source=customer&utm_campaign=p_lico+share-sheet

shared_text:
County of Santa Clara Public Health Department
June 24 at 9:05 AM ·

This global health crisis has changed life as we know it, especially for young children and teens.

Today at 10am, Uplift Family Services will talk about the emotional needs and risks for young children and teens since Shelter-in-Place has started. This segment will highlight when worry turns into anxiety and when anger and sadness can become depression. Our guest will provide information on how to talk to kids and when and how to get support. Also, we will discuss suicide and Santa Clara County data which DOES NOT support higher cases since sheltering in place.

Join us Monday, Wednesday, and Friday on Facebook Live at 10AM PT for the latest information on COVID-19.

Full transcripts will be made available after the live stream and will be linked under the video description.

SAMP, a regional nonprofit organization founded by #MilpitasHS student Rajvee Patel, has launched its newest initiative, titled “Project Connect,” which involves connecting students with the elderly in community with online sessions where high school students lead older adults in various activities such as meditation, games, technology tutorials, etc.

Students can receive community service hours for participation. Sign up at tinyurl.com/sampsessions.

In addition, #SAMP will host online sessions where we invite professionals, college students, etc. pursuing various careers to talk to students about their field. Students can ask questions to help gain more insight into a specific career of interest. Sign up at tinyurl.com/sampspeakers.

Hello #MUSDFamily and Community,

Today, we commemorate Juneteenth, the 155th year anniversary of the Emancipation Proclamation ending slavery in America. The struggle for freedom from oppression and racism continues, especially for those of African Ancestry. Building a Culture of We is about cultural sustainability and inclusion, and the more we know about one another’s history, the deeper our relationships in community become.

In unity,

Cheryl Jordan

#MUSD Superintendent

Learn more about #Juneteenth with this link:
https://nmaahc.si.edu/blog-post/celebrating-juneteenth

Why the #2020CensusMatters for Local Schools: The results of the 2020 Census will inform decisions about allocating hundreds of billions of dollars in federal funding to communities across the country. That includes funding and support for school programs and services such as:

Special education
Free and reduced-price lunch
Classroom technology
Teacher training
After-school programs
Head Start

This federal funding also supports services that influence a student's readiness for learning, such as maternal and child health programs, as well as housing, heating, and food assistance.

Get counted today at https://2020census.gov

WE are #MUSDfamily and WE will help one another to get through this together!

The County of Santa Clara is requiring everyone to wear a reusable cloth face covering whenever you are at any business, such as a grocery store or pharmacy, including those that are outdoors.

Growing evidence from the CDC suggests an estimated 25% of carriers show no symptoms. Wearing a face covering will help prevent the spread of coronavirus even when symptoms are not present.

Please do not use new medical-grade masks (N-95 respirators and surgical masks). These are in short supply and should be used by healthcare professionals who need them in order to continually provide care for our community.

Need additional information? Follow face covering guidance provided at: https://www.sccgov.org/sites/covid19/Pages/learn-what-to-do.aspx#howto

WE are #MUSDfamily and WE will help one another to get through this together!

shared_text:
County of Santa Clara Public Health Department
May 18 at 8:05 PM ·

Because of the substantial progress our community has achieved in slowing the spread of COVID-19, our Health Officer Dr. Sara Cody has issued an updated Shelter-in-Place order that will allow certain additional businesses and activities to resume. The new order goes into effect this Friday, May 22.

The new order allows retailers to provide curbside pickup services and also allows certain additional outdoor activities, including car parades, outdoor museums, historical sites, and public gardens.

We must all continue to stay home as much as possible, continue with to wear face coverings, and practice social distancing when in public. This is what has helped our region make progress to slow the spread of COVID-19. Read the new order: https://www.sccgov.org/sites/covid19/Pages/order-health-officer-05-18-20.aspx

post_text: County Health Officials plan to extend the Shelter in Place Order through May. Read press release below:
shared_text:
County of Santa Clara Public Health Department
April 27 at 11:59 AM ·

Today, Bay Area Health Officers announced that details about the next phase of the shelter-in-place orders will be provided later this week, that shelter-in-place will continue through May, and that it will include limited easing of specific restrictions for a small number of lower-risk activities. The Health Officers will also release a set of broad indicators to track progress on COVID-19 preparedness and response, in alignment with the framework used by the State of California. Press release available here: https://www.sccgov.org/sites/covid19/Pages/press-release-04-27-2020-joint-statement-on-extension-and-revisions.aspx

post_text:
Dear #MUSD Families,

We will be adding weekend meals to our service. Students will now have breakfast and lunch covered for 7 days!

Starting April 23rd and every Thursday, families will be able to pick up additional meals for the weekend. Our service will remain twice a week (Mondays & Thursdays) at 4 locations from 9:00 am - 12 noon. Please pick up meals at one of the four locations only:

--Milpitas High School, 1285 Escuela Parkway. Meal distribution is in the main cafeteria by the J Building.
--MUSD Board Room, 1331 E. Calaveras Blvd.
--Spangler Elementary, 140 N. Abbott Ave. Meal distribution is outside of the multi-use room on Rudyard Dr.
--Randall Elementary, 1300 Edsel Dr. Meal distribution is outside of the multi-use room.

We will have staff regulating lines and limiting the number of entries at each time to allow social distancing. Please come prepared with a large box or bags for easy take out.

#MUSDfamily

Even though we are sheltering in place, the Census 2020 count is moving forward. Census Day is April 1. #MUSD encourages our #MUSDfamily to participate in the Census because:

--Data collected in the census is used for the appropriation of over $675 billion in annual federal funding and apportionment for the House of Representatives; and

--Census results help determine how money is allocated for the Head Start program and for grants that support teachers and special education

Please complete your Census forms online at www.my2020census.gov or by toll-free phone call at 844-330-2020. Get counted today!

The Santa Clara County Census Office has created this informational video:
https://www.facebook.com/SCCcensus/posts/658198604936248

Please enjoy the day with your loved ones as we continue to Shelter in Place. EducatEverywhere flexible learning program will continue Tuesday, March 31.

Additionally, in coordination with the City of Milpitas, we have temporarily closed all #MUSD playgrounds and basketball courts to the public so we can work together to flatten the curve and slow the spread of the coronavirus (COVID-19) in our community.

post_text:
Governor waives state testing requirement for 2019-20

Attention MUSD Families and Team Members,

With the coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic forcing school closures throughout the state and across the country, Governor Gavin Newsom issued an executive order today suspending the state testing requirement for 2019-20.

The executive order states: “It is hereby ordered that Education Code section 6064 (a), requiring that all pupils be administered academic assessments in mathematics, English language arts, and science, as provided for in Education Code section 60640, is waived for the 2019-20 school year for all schools in the state for which the United States Department of Education approves, based on the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on students and school communities throughout California, a federal waiver of requirements to administer those academic assessments.”

This news allows us to focus on providing our students with the best learning opportunities we can within our MUSD Educate Everywhere program.

In community,

Office of the Superintendent
text:
Governor waives state testing requirement for 2019-20

Attention MUSD Families and Team Members,

With the coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic forcing school closures throughout the state and across the country, Governor Gavin Newsom issued an executive order today suspending the state testing requirement for 2019-20.

The executive order states: “It is hereby ordered that Education Code section 6064 (a), requiring that all pupils be administered academic assessments in mathematics, English language arts, and science, as provided for in Education Code section 60640, is waived for the 2019-20 school year for all schools in the state for which the United States Department of Education approves, based on the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on students and school communities throughout California, a federal waiver of requirements to administer those academic assessments.”

This news allows us to focus on providing our students with the best learning opportunities we can within our MUSD Educate Everywhere program.

In community,

Office of the Superintendent

post_text:
The Girls on the Run and Heart & Sole Program started last week at #SinnottElementary. This is the 5th year that the Girls on the Run #GOTR program has been at Sinnott. While the Girls on the Run is for second through fourth grade students, the inaugural Heart & Soles (H&S) is for fifth and sixth grade girls.

This program has trained coaches (volunteers) that lead girls through lessons about standing up for yourself and others, managing emotions, setting goals, stopping gossip and bullying, and so much more.

Teachers say they see the positive effects of GOTR girls' performance in the classroom, too! The program culminates with girls positively impacting their communities through a service project and being physically and emotionally prepared to complete the celebratory Girls on the Run / Heart & Sole 5K event at Vasona Park.

#MUSDfamily

Contact information for your school can be found at https://www.musd.org/schools.html. To learn more about new student registration, please visit our Enrollment page at https://www.musd.org/enrollment.html.

Transitional Kindergarten is being offered at #Burnett, #Randall, #Rose, #Pomeroy and #Spangler for the 2020-21 school year. Families will be notified by mail of school placement in July, prior to the beginning of school in August 2020. For more FAQs on TK, please visit our Enrollment page at https://www.musd.org/enrollment.html.

This Thursday (2/27) at 6:30pm, we will be showing the documentary Screenagers The Next Chapter: Uncovering Skills for Stress Resilience. It's "a film that examines the science behind teen’s emotional challenges, the interplay of social media, and most importantly, what can be done in our schools and homes to help them build crucial skills to navigate stress, anxiety, and depression in our digital age."

To learn more about the film, visit the FREE RSVP link http://bit.ly/2VpEyJj on the flyer where you can view the trailer. There will also be a panel of mental health experts and students to answer questions after the documentary.

The screening will be held at the SJCC College Extension, 1450 Escuela Parkway.

At Milpitas Unified School District, our educators share a growth mindset when it comes to our student outcomes in the classroom as well as on state standardized tests. Simply, we want to see improvement over time for each student as they work to meet and then exceed the state standard.

While MUSD students consistently outscore their county and state peers on standardized tests, this is only a one-moment-in-time assessment of our student achievement. However, our cohort data proves that as students move through our MUSD system, they are exhibiting year over year, statistically significant growth in English Language Arts and Mathematics.

https://drive.google.com/a/musd.org/file/d/1HgG19C_zIQPrGv8oiM5CZiWsXTNdUZAD/view?usp=sharing

Good evening MUSD Families and Team Members,

Today, the Santa Clara County Public Health Department released a video message from Public Health Officer Dr. Sara Cody regarding the Novel Coronavirus. This is a timely message about extending compassion, and remembering that a person should not be excluded from any activity on the basis of culture, ethnicity, or race. To view the video, click this link: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1waEVYjBOwM&feature=youtu.be

We will continue to provide our community with the latest Coronavirus information from the County Public Health Department.

The safety and health of all our students and staff remains our top priority! For those students and staff members who have recently traveled to China, we will continue to ask them to self-quarantine at home, and students will continue learning through our Short-term Independent Study Program.

For FAQs on the Coronavirus, please go to our web page: https://www.musd.org/information-and-updates-regarding-novel-coronavirus.html.

In community,

MUSD Leadership

post_text:
Attention Curtner and Spangler Families,

Power remains out at Curtner Elementary School as of this evening. PG&E has assigned a crew and will be investigating, but does not have an estimated time for restoration. Power has been restored at Spangler Elementary School.

We plan to have school in session tomorrow, and will follow our procedures for power outages to ensure the safety of our students and staff while maintaining a healthy learning environment for all.

Previously, during the October power outage, Curtner teachers noted that some students were brought flashlights, which made them feel a part of the solution. If you would like to send in a small flashlight for personal use your child is welcome to do so.

We will provide any further updates on Monday morning as we get them from PG&E.

Please note, while some families in the Spangler attendance are without power, Spangler school DOES have power. The electrical grids do not always coincide with attendance areas.

In Community,

MUSD Leadership

Milpitas Unified School District will continue to supply you with the latest from our county health officials as the information becomes available.

Hello MUSD families and friends,

We are excited to share the news that special guests County Supervisor David Cortese, Assemblymember Kansen Chu, and County Office of Education Board President Claudia Rossi will join Superintendent Cheryl Jordan, Board President Hon Lien, Board Vice President Chris Norwood, Mayor Rich Tran and Vice Mayer Bob Nunez for Monday evening's Milpitas "On the Table" Conversation Part 2.

We can't wait to see everyone at this special community engagement. Limited tickets are still available so please pull up a seat and join us for the Milpitas "On the Table" Conversation Part 2.
